{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=May 2018}} [[File:Inside Chinese temple.JPG|thumb|150px|The divinity [[Guan Yu]] enshrined in the Toong On Church of [[Kolkata]], [[India]].]] [[File:Nam Soon Church 06.JPG|thumb|150px|The Gods enshrined in the Nam Soon Church of Kolkata, India.]] '''Chinese temples''' are sacred sites for the practice of [[Chinese folk religion]]. [[Kolkata]] has a significant population of Indian nationals of [[Chinese community in India|Chinese ethnic origin]] (immigrants and their descendants that emigrated from China starting in the late 18th century to work at the [[Port of Kolkata|Kolkata port]] as well as the [[Chennai port]]). Unofficial estimates puts the population of Indian nationals of Chinese-origin in Kolkata anywhere from 5,000 to 200,000, most of whom live in or near [[Chinatown, Calcutta|Tangra]].<ref name="Banglapedia">{{cite book |last=Ray |first=Haraprasad |year=2012 |chapter=Chinese, The |chapter-url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Chinese,_The |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref><ref name="IPS News">{{cite web| last = Biswas| first = Ranjita| year = 2005| url = http://www.ipsnews.net/print.asp?idnews=30346| title = Little China Stays Alive in Eastern India| accessdate = 26 September 2006| work = IPS News| publisher = Inter Press Service News Agency| quote=Though most of the local Chinese are Christians, they celebrate the traditional Chinese New Year with gusto and many who emigrated from Kolkata make it a point to return at this time.}}</ref> The Chinese brought with them their culture. At least eight of the Chinese temples are located in the old Chinatown around Tiretta Bazar in Central Kolkata.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jaideep|first=Majumdar|title=A walk to unravel the confluence of cultures in Kolkata|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-01-17/kolkata/30634642_1_chinese-vendors-parsi-fire-temple-kolkata|accessdate=2 April 2013|newspaper=Times of India|date=17 January 2012}}</ref>
==Temples== Though the places of worship are referred to as "churches", they are sites of veneration that adhere to [[Chinese traditional religion]] and have nothing to do with Christianity. * Sea Ip Church (四邑會館) * Toong On Church (東安會館) * Choonghee Dong Thien Haue Church * Gee Hing Church * Sea Voi Yune Leong Futh Church (會寧會館) * Nam Soon Church (南順會館)
