{{refimprove|date=May 2015}}
The '''Dumalla''' or full name '''Chand Tora Dumalla''' is the style of [[turban]] generally worn by [[Nihang]] [[Khalsa]] [[Sikh]]s. This is a [[warrior]] style turban which was worn by Sikhs in battle. The "Chand Tora" is a metal symbol consisting of a crescent sword and a double edged sword, it is held in place at the front of the turban by a woven [[chainmail]] cord tied in a pattern within the turban to protect the head from slashing weapons.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Guides|first1=Insight|title=Insight Guides: India|date=2013|publisher=APA|location=London|isbn=1-78005-687-7|edition=Tenth|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fKsxBgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT302&dq=Dumalla&pg=PT302#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> [[File:Sikh triditional turban Dumalla.jpg|thumb|Sikh wearing a Dumalla]]
==Symbolism==
===The Tora=== The purpose of the "Tora" is to keep the [[dastaar]] together. It goes over the bunga to protect it and protect the dasam dwar. Also used for keeping shastars together.
