{{Politics of Latvia}}
The '''Jewish National Bloc''' ({{lang-lv|Ebreju nacionālais bloks}}) was a political alliance in [[Latvia]] in the 1920s. It consisted of Histadruth Hacionith, the Jewish National Democratic Party and [[Mizrachi (Latvia)|Mizrachi]].<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip Stöver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p1134 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref>
==History== The bloc contested the [[Latvian Constitutional Assembly election, 1920|1920 Constitutional Assembly elections]] as the '''Jewish Bloc''', winning five seats.<ref>Nohlen & Stöver, p1137</ref> For the [[Latvian parliamentary election, 1922|1922 elections]] it changed its name to the '''Jewish National Bloc''', but won only two seats in the [[1st Saeima]]. The bloc was later disbanded, with the three parties contesting the [[Latvian parliamentary election, 1925|1925 elections]] alone. Mizrachi won a single seat in the [[2nd Saeima]], whilst the other two failed to pass the [[electoral threshold]].
